{"title_page": "I Married a Woman", "text_new": "{{short description|1958 American comedy film by Hal Kanter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Married a Woman\n| image          = I Married a Woman.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Hal Kanter]]\n| producer       = William Bloom\n| writer         = [[Goodman Ace]]\n| starring       = [[George Gobel]]<br>[[Diana Dors]]<br>[[Adolphe Menjou]]\n| music          = [[Cyril J. Mockridge|Cyril Mockridge]]\n| cinematography = [[Lucien Ballard]]\n| editing        = Kennie Marstella\n| studio         = [[RKO Radio Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal-International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1958|5|14|ref1=<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=52604| title=I Married a Woman: Detail View | publisher=American Film Institute | accessdate= June 2, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''I Married a Woman''''' is a 1958 American [[comedy film]] made in 1956, starring [[George Gobel]] and [[Diana Dors]], produced by Gobel's company Gomalco Productions. The film also features [[John Wayne]] in a [[Cameo appearance|cameo role]] as himself. It was filmed in [[RKO]]-Scope and [[Black-and-white movie|black and white]] except for one of Wayne's two scenes, which was shot in [[Technicolor]]. The film's original title was \"So There You Are\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ioItAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZpkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5080,1171560&dq=goodman+ace |title=Helen Hayes to Perform in Film of 'Anastasia'|date=May 5, 1956|work=The Montreal Gazette|accessdate=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAdvertising executive Mickey Briggs is given 48 hours by his boss, Sutton, to come up with a [[Advertising campaign|campaign]] for client Luxemberg Beer and save the company from ruin. Mickey neglects his wife, Janice, who once had been a \"Miss Luxemberg\" in a successful ad campaign featuring various attractive models.\n\nJanice has just discovered she is expecting a baby, but is unable to inform Mickey, who is too distracted by work. Even when they find time to go to a movie, [[John Wayne]] is on screen, being considerate to his screen wife ([[Angie Dickinson]]), which makes Janice weepy but Mickey finds unrealistic.\n\nIt does give Mickey an idea, however, for a campaign in which \"Miss Luxemberg\" is now \"Mrs. Luxemberg\", enjoying family bliss. Sutton loves it, then rejects all the applicants until he decides that Janice herself must return to be \"Mrs. Luxemberg\". Film footage of their real life is shot without Janice's knowledge.\n\nAll goes terribly wrong, with Janice instead suing Mickey for [[divorce]] and Sutton's company for $100,000. After flirting with Mickey's wife, best pal Bob Sanders breaks the news that she's pregnant, which makes Mickey try harder to win her back. On a cruise and in love again, the couple is startled to spot John Wayne on board, arguing with his wife. \n\n==Cast==\n{| width=\"67%\"\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" valign=\"top\" |\n* [[George Gobel]] as Marshall \"Mickey\" Briggs\n* [[Diana Dors]] as Janice Blake Briggs aka Miss Luxemberg\n* [[Adolphe Menjou]] as Frederick W. Sutton\n* [[Jessie Royce Landis]] as Marshall's mother-in-law\n* [[Nita Talbot]] as Miss Anderson, Briggs' secretary\n* [[William Redfield (actor)|William Redfield]] as Eddie Benson, elevator operator\n* [[Stephen Dunne (actor)|Stephen Dunne]] as Bob Sanders\n* [[John McGiver]] as Girard, Sutton's lawyer\n* [[Steve Pendleton]] as photographer trailing Briggs\n* [[John Wayne]] as himself ''(uncredited)''\n| width=\"20%\" valign=\"top\" |\n[[Image:Diana Dors in I Married a Woman trailer.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Diana Dors]] in ''I Married a Woman'' film trailer]]\n|}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on an original story by New York radio writer and producer, Goodman Ace. In September 1950 the screen rights were bought by [[Norman Krasna]] and [[Jerry Wald]], who had a production deal at RKO.<ref>MONOGRAM LISTS 40 FILMS FOR YEAR: Rod Cameron to Star in Two Gold Banner Productions in Cinecolor at Studios Wald, Krasna Buy Ace Story\nNew York Times 6 Sep 1950: 48. </ref> They wanted to cast [[Cary Grant]] and [[Betsy Drake]].<ref>FILMLAND BRIEFS\nLos Angeles Times 21 Sep 1950: B13. </ref> In October [[Richard Fleischer]] was assigned the job of directing.<ref>SCREEN DIRECTORS WILL MEET ON ROW: Members to Hear Mankiewicz Give His Views on Sunday-- Recall Count Is Pending\nBy THOMAS F. BRADY New York Times 17 Oct 1950: 39. </ref> In November [[Celeste Holm]] was announced as star.<ref>Celeste Holm to Leave Play and Do a Movie: Looking at Hollywood\nHopper, Hedda. Chicago Daily Tribune 16 Nov 1950: c6. </ref> Ace was brought to Hollywood to work on a script, which Krasna wanted to aim at the female audience.<ref>HOLLYWOOD IN REVIEW: 'When I Leave World' Was Jolson Song in '14\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 29 Oct 1950: D6. </ref> In December 1950 RKO announced the film would be made the following year.<ref>RKO TO MAKE 32 TOP-BUDGET FILMS: One-Third of Scheduled 1951 Productions to Be Shot in Color, Executive Announces\nLos Angeles Times 5 Dec 1950: A7. </ref>\n\nHowever production kept being put back. In February Wald and Krasna said the film would be made in August, with Stanley Rubin as producer, but the film had no star or director.<ref>RKO Prepares to Start Films Costing 10 Million Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]05 Feb 1951: 22. </ref> In September 1951 Wald and Krasna said they had a script, and wanted to cast [[Cary Grant]] but wanted to get the casting right.<ref>Pair Cite Need for Film Flair: Krasna and Wald See Showmanship, Exciting Personalities as Essential Schallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 23 Sep 1951: D1. </ref> Wald and Krasna eventually left RKO.\n\nThe project was reactivated a number of years later. In April 1956, Diana Dors signed to play the female lead opposite TV star George Gobell.<ref>British Monroe Accepts U.S. Job Louella Parsons:; International News Service. The Washington Post and Times Herald 28 May 1956: 19. </ref> Her fee was $75,000 plus expenses.<ref>Drama: 'Old Yeller' Will Be Walt Disney Picture Los Angeles Times 16 July 1956: 26. </ref> It was Gobel's second leading roll after ''The Birds and the Bees''.\n\nDors arrived in the US in late June.<ref>Diana Dors, England's Reply to Monroe, Here: Calls Marilyn 'Greatest Thing That Ever Happened;' Plans Film With George Gobel Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]30 June 1956: 3. </ref> The job of directing was given to Hal Kanter, who worked with Gobel in television.\n\nFilming took place in July 1956. Kanter called the film \"light and frothy. It gave Goodman Ace... the chance to unload a lot of witty barbs he's been saving up over the years.\"<ref>HOLLYWOOD CANVAS: A JAPANESE BOY AND HIS HORSE AND COMIC COWBOYS ON VIEW THIS WEEK By OSCAR GODBOUT. New York Times 22 July 1956: X5. </ref>\n\nGobell called Dors \"a fine performer\".<ref>\"LONELY GEORGE TOO BUSY NOW TO GET LONELY\". Thomas, Bob. ''Chicago Daily Tribune'', 19 Aug 1956: n8. </ref> During filming RKO signed Dors to make a second film, ''The Lady and the Prowler'', which became ''The Unholy Wife''.<ref>\"DIANA DORS SIGNS PACT WITH R.K.O.: British Actress Will Appear in 'Lady and the Prowler' --Aldrich Picks 2d Film Of Local Origin\" By OSCAR GODBOUT. ''The New York Times'', 19 July 1956: 31.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[John Wayne filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0051757}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Married A Woman}}\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about advertising]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hal Kanter]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Cyril J. Mockridge]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:RKO Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1958 American comedy film by Hal Kanter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Married a Woman\n| image          = I Married a Woman.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Hal Kanter]]\n| producer       = William Bloom\n| writer         = [[Goodman Ace]]\n| starring       = [[George Gobel]]<br>[[Diana Dors]]<br>[[Adolphe Menjou]]\n| music          = [[Cyril J. Mockridge|Cyril Mockridge]]\n| cinematography = [[Lucien Ballard]]\n| editing        = Kennie Marstella\n| studio         = [[RKO Radio Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal-International]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1958|5|14|ref1=<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=52604| title=I Married a Woman: Detail View | publisher=American Film Institute | accessdate= June 2, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''I Married a Woman''''' is a 1958 American [[comedy film]] made in 1956, starring [[George Gobel]] and [[Diana Dors]], produced by Gobel's company Gomalco Productions. The film also features [[John Wayne]] in a [[Cameo appearance|cameo role]] as himself. It was filmed in [[RKO]]-Scope and [[Black-and-white movie|black and white]] except for one of Wayne's two scenes, which was shot in [[Technicolor]]. The film's original title was \"So There You Are\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ioItAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZpkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5080,1171560&dq=goodman+ace&hl=en|title=Helen Hayes To Perform In Film Of 'Anastasia'|date=May 5, 1956|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|accessdate=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAdvertising executive Mickey Briggs is given 48 hours by his boss, Sutton, to come up with a [[Advertising campaign|campaign]] for client Luxemberg Beer and save the company from ruin. Mickey neglects his wife, Janice, who once had been a \"Miss Luxemberg\" in a successful ad campaign featuring various attractive models.\n\nJanice has just discovered she is expecting a baby, but is unable to inform Mickey, who is too distracted by work. Even when they find time to go to a movie, [[John Wayne]] is on screen, being considerate to his screen wife ([[Angie Dickinson]]), which makes Janice weepy but Mickey finds unrealistic.\n\nIt does give Mickey an idea, however, for a campaign in which \"Miss Luxemberg\" is now \"Mrs. Luxemberg,\" enjoying family bliss. Sutton loves it, then rejects all the applicants until he decides that Janice herself must return to be \"Mrs. Luxemberg.\" Film footage of their real life is shot without Janice's knowledge.\n\nAll goes terribly wrong, with Janice instead suing Mickey for [[divorce]] and Sutton's company for $100,000. After flirting with Mickey's wife, best pal Bob Sanders breaks the news that she's pregnant, which makes Mickey try harder to win her back. On a cruise and in love again, the couple is startled to spot John Wayne on board, arguing with his wife. \n\n==Cast==\n{| width=\"67%\"\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" valign=\"top\" |\n* [[George Gobel]] as Marshall \"Mickey\" Briggs\n* [[Diana Dors]] as Janice Blake Briggs aka Miss Luxemberg\n* [[Adolphe Menjou]] as Frederick W. Sutton\n* [[Jessie Royce Landis]] as Marshall's mother-in-law\n* [[Nita Talbot]] as Miss Anderson, Briggs' secretary\n* [[William Redfield (actor)|William Redfield]] as Eddie Benson, elevator operator\n* [[Stephen Dunne (actor)|Stephen Dunne]] as Bob Sanders\n* [[John McGiver]] as Girard, Sutton's lawyer\n* [[Steve Pendleton]] as photographer trailing Briggs\n* [[John Wayne]] as himself ''(uncredited)''\n| width=\"20%\" valign=\"top\" |\n[[Image:Diana Dors in I Married a Woman trailer.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Diana Dors]] in ''I Married a Woman'' film trailer]]\n|}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on an original story by New York radio writer and producer, Goodman Ace. In September 1950 the screen rights were bought by [[Norman Krasna]] and [[Jerry Wald]], who had a production deal at RKO.<ref>MONOGRAM LISTS 40 FILMS FOR YEAR: Rod Cameron to Star in Two Gold Banner Productions in Cinecolor at Studios Wald, Krasna Buy Ace Story\nNew York Times 6 Sep 1950: 48. </ref> They wanted to cast [[Cary Grant]] and [[Betsy Drake]].<ref>FILMLAND BRIEFS\nLos Angeles Times 21 Sep 1950: B13. </ref> In October [[Richard Fleischer]] was assigned the job of directing.<ref>SCREEN DIRECTORS WILL MEET ON ROW: Members to Hear Mankiewicz Give His Views on Sunday-- Recall Count Is Pending\nBy THOMAS F. BRADY New York Times 17 Oct 1950: 39. </ref> In November [[Celeste Holm]] was announced as star.<ref>Celeste Holm to Leave Play and Do a Movie: Looking at Hollywood\nHopper, Hedda. Chicago Daily Tribune 16 Nov 1950: c6. </ref> Ace was brought to Hollywood to work on a script, which Krasna wanted to aim at the female audience.<ref>HOLLYWOOD IN REVIEW: 'When I Leave World' Was Jolson Song in '14\nSchallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 29 Oct 1950: D6. </ref> In December 1950 RKO announced the film would be made the following year.<ref>RKO TO MAKE 32 TOP-BUDGET FILMS: One-Third of Scheduled 1951 Productions to Be Shot in Color, Executive Announces\nLos Angeles Times 5 Dec 1950: A7. </ref>\n\nHowever production kept being put back. In February Wald and Krasna said the film would be made in August, with Stanley Rubin as producer, but the film had no star or director.<ref>RKO Prepares to Start Films Costing 10 Million Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]05 Feb 1951: 22. </ref> In September 1951 Wald and Krasna said they had a script, and wanted to cast [[Cary Grant]] but wanted to get the casting right.<ref>Pair Cite Need for Film Flair: Krasna and Wald See Showmanship, Exciting Personalities as Essential Schallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times 23 Sep 1951: D1. </ref> Wald and Krasna eventually left RKO.\n\nThe project was reactivated a number of years later. In April 1956, Diana Dors signed to play the female lead opposite TV star George Gobell.<ref>British Monroe Accepts U.S. Job Louella Parsons:; International News Service. The Washington Post and Times Herald 28 May 1956: 19. </ref> Her fee was $75,000 plus expenses.<ref>Drama: 'Old Yeller' Will Be Walt Disney Picture Los Angeles Times 16 July 1956: 26. </ref> It was Gobel's second leading roll after ''The Birds and the Bees''.\n\nDors arrived in the US in late June.<ref>Diana Dors, England's Reply to Monroe, Here: Calls Marilyn 'Greatest Thing That Ever Happened;' Plans Film With George Gobel Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]30 June 1956: 3. </ref> The job of directing was given to Hal Kanter, who worked with Gobel in television.\n\nFilming took place in July 1956. Kanter called the film \"light and frothy. It gave Goodman Ace... the chance to unload a lot of witty barbs he's been saving up over the years.\"<ref>HOLLYWOOD CANVAS: A JAPANESE BOY AND HIS HORSE AND COMIC COWBOYS ON VIEW THIS WEEK By OSCAR GODBOUT. New York Times 22 July 1956: X5. </ref>\n\nGobell called Dors \"a fine performer.\"<ref>LONELY GEORGE TOO BUSY NOW TO GET LONELY Thomas, Bob. Chicago Daily Tribune 19 Aug 1956: n8. </ref> During filming RKO signed Dors to make a second film, ''The Lady and the Prowler'', which became ''The Unholy Wife''.<ref>DIANA DORS SIGNS PACT WITH R.K.O.: British Actress Will Appear in 'Lady and the Prowler' --Aldrich Picks 2d Film Of Local Origin By OSCAR GODBOUT Special to The New York Times. New York Times 19 July 1956: 31. </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[John Wayne filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0051757}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Married A Woman}}\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[